In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle events API** in your `MauiProgram.cs` (or `App.xaml.cs`) via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;

public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

    builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
    {
#if ANDROID
        events.AddAndroid(android => android
            .OnPause(activity => { /* your code */ })
            .OnStop(activity => { /* your code */ }));
#elif IOS
        events.AddiOS(ios => ios
            .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* your code */ }));
#endif
    });

    return builder.Build();
}
```

**Key points:**

- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code conditional.
- `AddAndroid` exposes `OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnResume`, `OnCreate`, etc.
- `AddiOS` exposes `DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, `OnActivated`, etc.
- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` for the extension methods.

See the [official docs](https://learn.microsoft.com/dotnet/maui/fundamentals/app-lifecycle) for the full list of mapped events per platform.
